Day 16 - One week until gold medal, 4 days until single digits.

Oh, hey soldiers! I dug out a small room here for us out in the trenches. Yeah, this mission is a little more complicated than what we're used to but I'm sure most of the veterans have been through this before. Let's take a moment to reconsider what we've done up to this point and how we should move forward.

We've survived 16 days soldiers, a little over 2 weeks. That's insanely impressive and I'm really happy that we've made it this far. I saw another soldier who goes by the name "OG2011" mention that it's only 5 more days until we count single digits... well, 4 now but always gotta look forward to the milestones right? After all, in 4 days we can count our victory by the single digits, since that comes before the gold medal let's focus on getting there first. When the days go into single digits the gold medal will be right around the corner anyway so that'll be a short milestone and from there it's just one week to the finish line.

I hope that made sense soldiers, but look forward to those next few milestones and focus on reaching the nearest one first. If we can do that we'll have more than enough motivation to win!

Anyway, get yourselves comfy because we're gonna be here for a while. In the morning we'll set out to finish the current mission and should get back to base around the afternoon, just in time for free pizza day. Have a good rest soldiers, we're gonna need it. Things should only go uphill from here, if The Chief won't promise that then I certainly will. Good luck soldiers, I'm always rooting for you! o7

The battles been tough but we're making it through day by day. To be honest this year I feel pretty bad, this is my first year working a full time contracted job so keeping up with the community has been really hard for me, and on top of my general awkwardness to talk to new people already, I've found it hard to talk in here again until now cuz I feel like I've missed out on everything, I'll try to do better from now on lol, but I can still share what it's been like up 'til now.  
This year's been a rough one for me, I don't know what it's been but this year the relapses from not nutting have hit way harder, like the first week or so was pretty easy, but about day 7/8 it reallyyy started to kick in and wayyyy stronger than ever before, and everyday it was really hard to fight against the urges and to resist the nut, but so far i've stayed strong, I've beaten this challenge the last 3 years, I can do it again.  
General life has also made it more difficult, I've had my job at my hospital get more intense with workload and relocation, I've gotten ill and had to stay home several days on top of that so I felt absolutely terrible, but honestly worst part about it all was watching my OG homie succumb to the nut. This dude was the one who introduced me to the challenge back in 2019 and we have subsequently beaten it every year since then, and to see such a prestige veteran in my eyes catch that 1 stray bullet and fall in battle besides me was.... disheartening to say the least.  


But nevertheless I will carry on the fight in his honour and everyone else who was fallen thus far, for we aren't alone in this my battle brothers, and we shall emerge victorious above all!

The air is thick with tension, the crew grumbles and complains about the horrors of the Zee and the life that they persue. Right now I have to do anything I can to raise the morale, or I fear that mutiny is inevitable. I need time to think.

I retreat to my quarters, looking at the information that the Admiralty asked me to retrieved. Names upon names of people who had visited the Chapel of Lights. I paused, these names seems familiar. Opening the drawers and pulling out another piece of information collected from Khan's Heart. Yes, everything starts to make sense now, and combined with the Zee-Ztory I've heard. Yes, the Admiralty must be happy with this Vital Intelligence. I blink, how much time has passed? I do not know; I need some fresh air.

I walked outside, the ship is silent. The air still feels thick and I can feel the lasting tension that lingers even without any crew around. On the starboard I spot a lonely zailor leaning on the railing, looking out at the Zee. I begin walking towards her before I spot a gleaming tentacle rising from the Zee. It coils lazily around the zailor, who does not speak or cry out. She only steps into its cold embrace and is gone.

I run to the place where the zailor previously stood, calling out her name. The Zee is quiet, nothing stirs. But I swear to the Gods that I saw the moon-paled limb of the monster... Was it there? Did she simply leap? Surely I didn't push her.
